Our team has completed our review of the contractor's Terraform landing zone code. Before we can provide any formal sign-off, I want to share our findings transparently, as there are several areas where the contractor's implementation diverges significantly from our established standards and architecture.

Below is a summary of what we've identified:

Configuration Management: The contractor is using Ansible for RBAC configuration in Kubernetes, as well as for deploying applications, setting up namespaces, resource quotas, and limit ranges. Our standard is to manage all of this through Terraform. Terraform gives us a single source of truth with full state tracking, auditability, and the ability to cleanly destroy resources when they're no longer needed. Introducing Ansible alongside Terraform fragments our IaC strategy and increases operational overhead.

EKS Worker Nodes: The contractor's implementation uses AL2023 for node AMIs. Our standard is Bottlerocket with FIPS compliance. This is a security and compliance requirement, not a preference.

Pod-Level IAM: The contractor is using IRSA (IAM Roles for Service Accounts). We have standardized on EKS Pod Identity, which is the AWS-recommended path forward and simplifies cross-account role management.

Networking: The contractor's implementation deploys a standalone VPC with arbitrary subnets and an Internet Gateway for egress. Our architecture routes all traffic through a Transit Gateway hub model. Direct IGW egress per account does not align with our network security posture and bypasses centralized traffic inspection and routing controls.

Deployment Pipeline: All code is being run via local CLI commands. Our team exclusively deploys through GitHub Actions. Any landing zone code that requires manual local execution is not viable for our operational model.

Taken individually, each of these might look like a preference. Taken together, they represent a fundamentally different architecture than what we've built and operate today. Adopting this code would mean maintaining two parallel approaches, which increases complexity, risk, and cost — or it would require us to rework the contractor's code so extensively that we'd essentially be rewriting it.

To be direct: our team has already developed and matured a landing zone that is in production and aligns with all of the standards above. We are not in a position to sign off on code that doesn't meet our operational and security requirements, and we would not plan to use this code in our environment.

Our recommendation is to discontinue the contractor's landing zone workstream to avoid further spend on a deliverable that will not be adopted. We're happy to walk through our existing landing zone with any stakeholders who'd like visibility into what's already in place.

